  <h2 id="faqs">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is AXA Global Healthcare accepted for French visa applications?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">
        Yes, AXA is typically well-accepted for French visa applications due to their French regulatory status. As an ACPR-regulated insurer, AXA policies often face fewer questions from French authorities than policies from non-EU insurers. However, always verify specific visa requirements with the French consulate, as requirements can vary by visa type.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How does AXA handle pre-existing conditions?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">
        AXA uses full medical underwriting, which means they review your health history and may exclude pre-existing conditions permanently or apply premium loading. Unlike Allianz Care (which offers moratorium underwriting), AXA doesn't have a "two-year moratorium" option. If you have significant pre-existing conditions, Allianz may provide better access to coverage.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I add or remove modules during my policy?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">
        You can typically add modules at policy renewal. Removing modules may also be possible at renewal, though some modules (like maternity) may require you to wait until a benefit period ends. Adding maternity mid-year would restart the 10-12 month waiting period. Contact AXA directly to discuss specific changes to your policy.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What happens if I move to a different country?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">
        AXA Global Healthcare is designed for mobility. If you move within your coverage area, your policy continues. Moving to a different coverage zone (e.g., from Europe-only to Worldwide) requires a policy change and potentially different premium. Moving to the US when you have "worldwide excluding USA" coverage would require upgrading your plan.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How good is AXA's US coverage compared to competitors?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">
        AXA's US coverage is adequate but not a strength. Their US network (400,000+ providers) is smaller than Aetna's integrated network, and direct billing is limited. You'll often pay upfront and get reimbursed. If the US is a major part of your life, Aetna International or GeoBlue offer significantly better US experiences.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is there an age limit for AXA Global Healthcare?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">
        AXA accepts new members up to age 74 for most plans. Existing members can renew beyond age 74, typically with continued coverage for life. Premiums increase with age, and some benefits may have age-related limits. Contact AXA for specific details about coverage at older ages.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="final-verdict">Final Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    AXA Global Healthcare is an excellent choice for <strong>expats in Europe</strong> who want comprehensive coverage from an EU-regulated insurer. Their French regulatory status provides tangible benefits for visa applications and policyholder protections that non-EU insurers can't match.
  </p>
  <p>
    The <strong>modular plan design</strong> gives you flexibility to build coverage that matches your exact needs, and the <strong>1.6 million+ provider network</strong> ensures access to quality care throughout Europe and Asia. Pricing is competitive for the European market, especially with higher deductible options offering up to 43% savings.
  </p>
  <p>
    However, AXA has limitations. <strong>US coverage is adequate but not optimal</strong>—if you need extensive US care, Aetna or GeoBlue serve you better. <strong>Pre-existing conditions are typically excluded</strong> under their full underwriting approach; Allianz's moratorium option may be more accepting. And if <strong>mental health is a priority</strong>, BUPA's full parity coverage exceeds what AXA offers on lower-tier plans.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Bottom line:</strong> If you live in Europe, need insurance for EU visa applications, and value regulatory protections, AXA Global Healthcare is a strong, reliable choice from one of the world's largest insurers.
  </p>

